  "body": "## Description\r\n\r\n[Announcing Rust 1.58.0 | Rust Blog](https://blog.rust-lang.org/2022/01/13/Rust-1.58.0.html)\r\n\r\n> ### Stabilized APIs\r\n> [File::options](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/std/fs/struct.File.html#method.options)\r\n\r\n\r\n`File::options` is stabilized in Rust 1.58.\r\n\r\nAs described in the [API document](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/std/fs/struct.File.html#method.options), `File::options` is equivalent to `OpenOptions::new()` but allows us to write more readable code, and also avoids the need to import `OpenOptions `.\r\n\r\n```diff\r\nuse std::fs::File;\r\n- use std::fs::OpenOptions;\r\n\r\nfn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {\r\n-    let mut f = OpenOptions::new().read(true).open(\"foo.txt\")?;\r\n+    let mut f = File::options().read(true).open(\"foo.txt\")?;\r\n    Ok(())\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n`OpenOptions::new` is used [here](https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/search?q=OpenOptions) so these can be replaced with `File::options`.",
